title: New name for ex-javagame topic till something better pops up
content:
Hi!
as the topic says I'm new here and this is my first post but I hope this doesn't stop anyone from replying [img]http://www.classicgaming.com/cc314/msgboard/emotikeen-smile.gif[/img]

I started to write a game in java for my mobile phone some week ago and it's in a state where little keen (sized for a small LCD) can jump, grab the ledge and of course pogo [img]http://www.classicgaming.com/cc314/msgboard/emotikeen-pogo.gif[/img] through the
test map. Would you like to see more of it as it evolves from a
mere jumping machine to a keen game? [img]http://www.classicgaming.com/cc314/msgboard/emotikeen-smile.gif[/img] I don't know how and
where to upload or link the jar file from. Of course I'll only do it if
you'd like me to.

I'd also like to ask you a few things about my game as well. You know, researching ideas [img]http://www.classicgaming.com/cc314/msgboard/emotikeen-smile.gif[/img] How the control layout would be on phone keys etc.

enough for now!

title: Re: heh
content:
Xky: I have nothing to do with the second image.

lv4n: That green soil looks like there's some kind of green slime on the road. I know that it would look strange to have patches of grass in the middle of a desert, but this is not desert, just a path in the grass.

Galaxieretter: Thanks for the support [img]http://www.classicgaming.com/cc314/msgboard/emotikeen-smile.gif[/img]

I don't think that the background doesn't match the character. The point exactly is to separate the background from the sprites to have some contrast, otherwise it'd be hard to notice your sprite on the screen. In many cartoons (maybe not those that are made nowadays with low budget) the background is painted while the characters look more like an outlined and colored image. This is what I try to archive in my game at the moment. If it doesn't work I can still change how many colors there are in the tiles, I can add outlines and make them look brighter etc. but I don't think it will come to that.

I won't post any more images till the first set of ground/underground tiles are ready with one background. After that I can create a new demo with hard work! (hard work=new map [img]http://www.classicgaming.com/cc314/msgboard/emotikeen-grin.gif[/img] )

title: Re: heh

title: Re: New name for ex-javagame topic till something better pop
content:
The system I'm using is where all in-game objects are derived from the gObject class. For example, you might have a gPointItem class which is derived from the gObject class. Whenever the player collided with it (invoking the gPointItem's collision() member function, a virtual function inherited from the gObject class) the gPointItem would call a function from the Game class to increment the player's score and then destroy itself, removing itself from the list of in-game objects and deallocating all its resources.

The Game class is a class that allows the main() loop and classes to access high-level game functions - such as increasing the score - without messing around in the internals of the game. For example, it might have an IncrementScore function that the gPointItem object would call to increase the score. How would the gPointItem know where the Game object was? Because it would be passed a pointer to the Game class in its constructor when it was created. It would store this pointer for later use.

I can make the newest source available for you if you wish, but I don't know how much help that'd be. Understanding other people's complicated source code is sometimes harder than making up something on your own.

This is the object hierarchy I use:
[img]http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v505/z-one/object-hierarchy.png[/img]

There is a main Manager and Map object, both accessible for everything. Every other object is owned by the Manager object, except the player. I handle everything for the player separately, because it is a special object in a way. There's a linked list for everything that is a tCharacter, and another one for the items Keen can collect.
Here's the game's main loop.
1. read keyboard input
2. while timer variable is more than 0 (to keep up the same speed on all machines) the Manager's next() function is called. (see bellow) and the timer variable is decremented.
3. call the Manager's paint() function
4. back to step 1.

Manager's next()
1. if reached the end of the level then quit
2. call map's next(). This changes the current frame for animated tiles
3. call move(). It places the player, the others, and the collectible items where they should be on the next step, while checking for collision between the player-monsters and everyone -map. This is gonna kill the player when needed too.
4. call advance(). change the player and the monsters current speed and velocity by gravity. check collision between player-items
5. call act(). check what key was pressed and make the player behave accordingly.
6. back to step 1

Manager's paint(). I use double buffer for drawing, so everything is first drawn to the buffer, and then the buffer is drawn on the speed. I use a memory buffer, not the video memory as it seems that reading from the video memory is slow (for translucency effects)
1. paint the map background layer on the buffer
2. paint the items
3. iterate through the monsters' linked list and paint every one of them that's on the screen at least a bit.
4. paint the player
5. paint the foreground layer on top of them
6. paint the particles. at the moment only the collected items' point indication, but there will be more later.
7. paint the score and ammo indicator, and the info messages like fps and others (there are others but I usually remove them from the demo, as they are there for debugging reasons only)

If you still aren't bored to death, I can tell you that I've tried to create a main object class as the ancestor of everything else, but it turned out to be useless and made more problems than what it solved, so I've abandoned the idea whatsoever. Objects are often useful for managing complicated ... objects that are related to each other, but making everything absolutely object oriented is a bad thing.

As you can see the main sprite class is the ancestor of everything that can move on the map, so it has functions and properties that they all share (mostly), like check_collision, paint, screen and map coordinates, change to next frame. The sprite class manages the frame bitmaps too.

Vitamin Zach: There's no connection between the switch and the tiles on the map, there's not really a switch either. The Map object loads the 3 layers of the map's tiles, loads the animated tiles' frames in a separate list and loads "actions" on another map layer. The one for the switch and anything else that's activated by pressing the "up" key is just one of the actions, that could do anything from making keen entering a door, acting like he is pressing a button, waiting some game ticks, replacing any tiles with any other tile or animated tile on the map, replacing actions with any other action on the map etc. The tile replacement is just another list, with the new tile number and the coordinates to place it.


1. between the player and monsters, yes, but it doesn't take as much time as it seems. I only check the player for collision with the items (at the moment).

2. I have a text file which holds a 'table' for the different states of the sprites for walking, jumping etc. Every state has one or more image names for it's frames, and every frame has it's own bounding rectanges defined in the file. Eg. when the player is in the walking state I simply repeat the frames for walking. I have a variable for the state and for the current frame in the state too...
